Pelvic.cor <- function(a, b) {
  a <- a
  b <- b
  p.cor <- cor(a, b)
  
  return(p.cor)
}

Pelvic.cor(DelPreteTW$Index_AP_inlet, DelPreteTW$Birthdate)
[1] -0.004330664

T tests and Wilcoxon Signed Rank Tests

Restoring the data set to the Terry Collection with both genders.

DelPrete <- read_excel("Delprete.xlsx")

# Changning data into a data frame

DelPrete <- as.data.frame(DelPrete)

DelPreteT <- subset(DelPrete, Collection_number != 1)
DelPreteT <- subset(DelPreteT, Collection_number != 2)
DelPreteT <- subset(DelPreteT, Collection_number != 3)
hist(DelPreteT$Index_AP_inlet)

hist(DelPreteT$Index_bispinous)

hist(DelPreteT$Index_TD_outlet)

hist(DelPreteT$Index_pelvic_breadth)

hist(DelPreteT$Index_AP_outlet)

The AP Inlet and Pelvic Breadth index values are the only two which is normally distributed, so we can use a t test. The responses are not normally distributed so we have to use a non parametric test.

?t.test
t.test(DelPreteT$Index_AP_inlet ~ DelPreteT$Ethnicity)

    Welch Two Sample t-test

data:  DelPreteT$Index_AP_inlet by DelPreteT$Ethnicity
t = 0.53506, df = 95.447, p-value = 0.5939
alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
95 percent confidence interval:
 -1.997273  3.471222
sample estimates:
mean in group B mean in group W 
       103.1919        102.4550 
t.test(DelPreteT$Index_pelvic_breadth ~ DelPreteT$Ethnicity)

    Welch Two Sample t-test

data:  DelPreteT$Index_pelvic_breadth by DelPreteT$Ethnicity
t = -2.5187, df = 95.196, p-value = 0.01345
alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
95 percent confidence interval:
 -4.0508172 -0.4798135
sample estimates:
mean in group B mean in group W 
       93.67232        95.93763

Since the p-value for the AP Inlet is greater than 0.05 we cannot conclude that there is a statistical difference between the mean AP Inlet index value of the races of the Terry collection. Since the p-value for the Pelvic Breadth is less than 0.05 we can conclude that there is a statistical difference between the mean Pelvic Breadth index value of the races of the Terry collection.


wilcox.test(DelPreteT$Index_bispinous ~ DelPreteT$Ethnicity)

    Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction

data:  DelPreteT$Index_bispinous by DelPreteT$Ethnicity
W = 1122, p-value = 0.5818
alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0
wilcox.test(DelPreteT$Index_TD_outlet ~ DelPreteT$Ethnicity)

    Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction

data:  DelPreteT$Index_TD_outlet by DelPreteT$Ethnicity
W = 1410, p-value = 0.1365
alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0
wilcox.test(DelPreteT$Index_AP_outlet ~ DelPreteT$Ethnicity)

    Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction

data:  DelPreteT$Index_AP_outlet by DelPreteT$Ethnicity
W = 1599, p-value = 0.004626
alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0

For the Bispinous and the TD Outlet index values we see that the p-value is greater than 0.05 so we cannot conclude that the ranks for each index value are different, respectively. For the AP Outlet index value we see that the p-value is less than 0.05 so we can conclude that there is a difference in the ranks of the two races in the Terry collection.
